
[1]polemoscope

   POLEM'OSCOPE, n. [Gr. war, and to view.] An oblique perspective glass
   contrived for seeing objects that do not lie directly before the eye.
   It consists of a concave glass placed near a plane mirror in the end of
   a short round tube, and a convex glass in a hole in the side of the
   tube. It is called opera-glass, or diagonal opera-glass.
